DATA 299: Sports Analytics - Hitchman

Load Data into your session from a .csv file

Here we consider some hitting statistics from Major League Baseball from the 2024 season (April to October, 2024). To load the data into your session, run the following code in your script

hit <- read.csv("https://mphitchman.com/stats/sports/data/hit24.csv")

Load the tidyverse into your session

library(tidyverse)

Recall, the tidyverse contains the useful packages

  • dplyr (action verbs!)
  • ggplot (plots)

Q2. Filter the data frame to include just those hitters that had at least 350 plate appearances (PA), and use ggplot to make a histogram of the WOBA variable. What is the mean of the WOBA values?

p <- ggplot(hit |> filter(PA >= 350))+
  geom_histogram(aes(x=WOBA),bins=18,col='white',fill='wheat')+
  ggtitle("WOBA for hitters in 2024 with at least 350 PA")
p

mean((hit |> filter(PA>=350))$WOBA)
## [1] 0.3187884
p + geom_vline(xintercept = mean((hit |> filter(PA>=350))$WOBA),col='red',linetype='dashed')

Q4. Make side-by-side boxplots for batting average (AVG) by batting type (left, right, or switch hitters). Do you notice any appreciable differences among these groups?

ggplot(hit |> filter(PA>=350),aes(x=Bats,y=AVG))+
  geom_boxplot()

Q5. Primary position

Create a new column that gives a players primary defensive position. We define a players primary position to be associated with the first number appearing in the Pos column, using the convention that

num position
2 catcher
3 first base
4 second base
5 third base
6 shortstop
7 left field
8 center field
9 right field
NA designated hitter 
hit$Pos[is.na(hit$Pos)]<-0
hit$Pos <- as.character(hit$Pos)
hit <- hit |> 
  mutate(prim_pos = substr(Pos,1,1)) |> 
  mutate(prim_pos = recode(
    prim_pos,
    '0'='dh',
    '2'='c',
    '3'='1b',
    '4'='2b',
    '5'='3b',
    '6'='ss',
    '7'='lf',
    '8'='cf',
    '9'='rf'))

Heres a glimpse at the resulting prim_pos column:

Q6. Restricting hitters to those with at least 350 plate appaearaces, use ggplot to construct side-by-side boxplots grouped by primary position for slugging percentage (SLG). Does the plot suggest that the big sluggers tend to be in the corner positions (RF, LF, 3B, 1B, and DH)?

ggplot(hit |> filter(PA>=350),aes(x=SLG,y=prim_pos))+
  geom_boxplot()+
  geom_jitter(aes(col=prim_pos))
